
Looking down the permissions you will see that they either start with 

(d) stands for a directory
(-) stands for a file

the next nine spaces indicate the persmissions granter for a owner, group and everyone

The options they have are: 
r (octal val 4)= read 
w (octal val 2)= write
x (octal val 1)= execute
none 0 



student@vagrant-ubuntu-trusty-64:~$ ls -al
total 32
drwxr-xr-x 4 student student 4096 Jan  4 06:33 .
drwxr-xr-x 5 root    root    4096 Jan  4 04:35 ..
-rw------- 1 student student  501 Jan  5 05:08 .bash_history
-rw-r--r-- 1 student student  220 Jan  4 04:35 .bash_logout
-rw-r--r-- 1 student student 3637 Jan  4 04:35 .bashrc
drwx------ 2 student student 4096 Jan  4 05:04 .cache
-rw-r--r-- 1 student student  675 Jan  4 04:35 .profile
drwx------ 2 student student 4096 Jan  4 06:43 .ssh 


chown
	changes the files owner
		sudo chown root .bash_history



chgrp
	changes the files group permissios
		sudo chgrp root .bash_history